                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\"><placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>\n                                        <date>13 Feby 5609</date>.</p>\n                              <p>Revd Sir</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Accept my thanks for inserting, in the\n                                        occident<lb/> of this month, my first letter on the union\n                                        &amp;c. It is thought much<lb/> of here, perhaps more than\n                                        it deserves. I am not over greedy of praise<lb/> but if my\n                                        labours contribute, in the smallest degree, to promote the\n                                        good<lb/> cause, it will I confess make me happy, and amply\n                                        compensate me.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I have now the pleasure of handing you Letter 3,\n                                        on<lb/> subjects confessedly difficult to be properly\n                                        treated. Whether I have succee=<lb/>=ded or not in my\n                                        expositions, and to what degree will be judged by the\n                                        public<lb/> before whom my letters are to be placed.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I read very attentively your excellent article on\n                                        “The<lb/> Results of Union.” it came very opportunely, and I\n                                        availed myself<lb/> of it, as you will perceive in my 3\n                                        Letter, to induce patient attention to<lb/> my exposition.\n                                        Your remarks and suggestions, and my two first letters<lb/>\n                                        ought to suffice for the purposes of the suggested meeting.\n                                        Our Folks<lb/> scarcely ever proceed at Railway speed,\n                                        therefore what you may further<lb/> suggest and I may\n                                        publish will be in very good time and keeping, even<lb/> if\n                                        issued after holding the meeting, for the Union should it\n                                        ever take<lb/> place. I shall therefore continue my\n                                        exposition, and though not as fully<lb/> as might be done, I\n                                        will still endeavour to render it as useful and\n                                        interesting<lb/> as I can, by neglecting nothing that I\n                                        think might conduce to those ends.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I expect the pleasure of a letter from you in\n                                        acknow=<lb/>ledgment of that I wrote you on forwarding to\n                                        you my 2<hi rend=\"sup\">nd</hi> Letter on the Union.<lb/> I\n                                        am anxious to learn if you approve of and intend, on my\n                                        suggestion, announcing<lb/> at once in the occident for\n                                                  <date><sic>march</sic></date>, the meeting for\n                                                  <date>Rosh Hodesh Sivan</date>, the<lb/>\n                                        <date>22<hi rend=\"sup\">nd</hi> May</date>, at <placeName>New\n                                                  York</placeName>. In your article “The results of\n                                        Union” page</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3q52fv9x/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
